<subsection xml:id="subsec-acceleration" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Acceleration</title>
    <objectives component="outcomes">
        <introduction xml:id="auto_az555whn">
            <dl>
                <li xml:id="auto_8n9oaglz">
                    <title>Strand</title>
                    <p xml:id="auto_po3y0vm1">
                        2.0 Measurements and Geometry
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_6cr47zue">
                    <title>Sub-Strand</title>
                    <p xml:id="auto_7fvyyem2">
                        2.10 Linear Motion
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_505f43kg">
                    <title>Specific Learning Outcomes</title>
                    <p xml:id="auto_otuo3qpy">
                        Explain the terms velocity and acceleration in real-life situations. Determine velocity and acceleration in different situations.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_mi4oe4ft" component="lesson-plan">
                    <title>Grade Level</title>
                    <p xml:id="auto_ish48a01">
                        10
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_2zixrw1q" component="lesson-plan">
                    <title>Estimated Duration</title>
                    <p xml:id="auto_81pf6rpd">
                        40 minutes
                    </p>
                </li>
            </dl>
            <p xml:id="auto_wy4y8gr8" component="lesson-plan">
                <p xml:id="auto_n0hxgvmo"> Upon completion of this lesson, learners will be able to:
                <ol>
                    <li xml:id="auto_1fei79p3">
                        <p xml:id="auto_4fc5l72s">
                            <alert>Know (Conceptual Understanding):</alert> Define acceleration as the rate of change of velocity with time. Understand that negative acceleration (deceleration/retardation) means the object is slowing down. Know the three equations of motion for constant acceleration.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_lsxb0w7a">
                        <p xml:id="auto_a57h8d8d">
                            <alert>Do (Procedural Skill):</alert> Apply the formula <m>a = \frac{\Delta v}{\Delta t}</m> to calculate acceleration. Use the three equations of motion (<m>v = u + at</m>, <m>s = ut + \frac{1}{2}at^2</m>, <m>v^2 = u^2 + 2as</m>) to solve problems.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_go9f6v8v">
                        <p xml:id="auto_bzj16rnf">
                            <alert>Apply (Application/Problem-Solving):</alert> Solve real-world problems involving acceleration such as vehicles braking, rockets launching, and objects speeding up or slowing down. Interpret the sign of acceleration in context.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
                </p>
            </p>
        </introduction>
    </objectives>
    <axiom component="resources">
        <!-- Link to blurb -->
        <xi:include href="../../resources-blurb-lesson.ptx" />

        <sbsgroup widths="45% 45%" margins="2% 2%">
            <sidebyside>
                <p xml:id="auto_8k7u1p64">
                    <dataurl source="lesson_plans/measurements-and-geometry/linear-motion/acceleration.pdf"> Lesson Plan </dataurl>
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_5ajra4ap">
                    <dataurl source="lesson_plans/measurements-and-geometry/linear-motion/step-by-step-guide_acceleration.pdf"> Step-by-Step Guide </dataurl>
                </p>
            </sidebyside>
        </sbsgroup>
    </axiom>
    <xi:include href="../../resources-materials.ptx" />

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Phase 1: Exploring Velocity and Acceleration</title>
        <dl>
            <li xml:id="auto_z69ngeh5">
                <title>Suggested Time</title>
                <p xml:id="auto_wuprn0ae">
                    15 minutes
                </p>
            </li>
            <li xml:id="auto_8px0yyer">
                <title>Grouping</title>
                <p xml:id="auto_sy3tf0j8">
                    Work in small groups (3<ndash/>4 students)
                </p>
            </li>
            <li xml:id="auto_iwhbtzkj">
                <title>Materials</title>
                <p xml:id="auto_unmwysd3">
                    Calculators, stopwatches, measuring tape, toy cars (optional)
                </p>
            </li>
            <li xml:id="auto_32t5u7hp">
                <title>Teacher's Role</title>
                <p xml:id="auto_o3hjidhx">
                    Circulate among groups as they work through the four tasks. For Task 1, encourage students to articulate definitions in their own words before formalising. For Tasks 2<ndash/>4, check that students are showing working and using correct units. Use student responses to bridge into the formal definitions.
                </p>
            </li>
            <li xml:id="auto_znwrnoev">
                <title>Discussion Questions</title>
                <p xml:id="auto_5i6zb8ks">
                    <ol marker="(a)">
                        <li xml:id="auto_lvysycnu"><p xml:id="auto_ug12kdii"><q>How did you calculate velocity? What formula did you use?</q></p></li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_pugz6chs"><p xml:id="auto_mwreuymt"><q>What is the difference between speed and velocity?</q></p></li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_6ndy5k9f"><p xml:id="auto_nb81bnss"><q>When the car is speeding up, what happens to acceleration?</q></p></li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_02m1mg3r"><p xml:id="auto_6nro4b4z"><q>When the car is slowing down (braking), is acceleration positive or negative?</q></p></li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_gq65l0cw"><p xml:id="auto_7uelmql7"><q>Can you think of real-life examples of positive and negative acceleration?</q></p></li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </li>
        </dl>
        <p xml:id="auto_c5mp8k6g">
            Identify 2<ndash/>3 groups with clear findings to share with the class.
        </p>
    </axiom>


    <activity xml:id="auto_cciu3uff">
        <p xml:id="auto_xqtjew12">
            <term>Work in groups</term>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_ytpahx0t">
            <ol xml:id="auto_ltng52um">
                <li xml:id="auto_9j9xdlt3">
                    <p xml:id="auto_ovpdpme6">
                         Define
                         <ol xml:id="auto_j6j46ohp" marker="a).">
                            <li xml:id="auto_6ctttrm3">
                                <p xml:id="auto_cntq7zej">
                                    Velocity
                                </p>
                            </li>
                            <li xml:id="auto_gvznn3j3">
                                <p xml:id="auto_ee9bdqh8">
                                    Velocity
                                </p>
                            </li>
                         </ol>
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_r1qz7p96">
                    <p xml:id="auto_n6qmwdni">
                        A car travels <m>200</m> meters in <m>10</m> seconds. What is its average velocity?
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_g9twb2ma">
                    <p xml:id="auto_l2gg1c9g">
                        A car accelerates from <m>75</m> km/h to <m>90</m> km/h in <m>10</m> seconds.
                    </p>
                    <p xml:id="auto_hxbg81bj">
                        Find it's acceleration
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_ypfht96n">
                    <p xml:id="auto_gjzi4q7s">
                        A vehicle moving at <m>\text{25 m/s}</m> applies brakes and comes to a stop in <m>\text{5 seconds}</m>.
                        <ol xml:id="auto_zyjhze1h" marker="a).">
                            <li xml:id="auto_92spdjqn">
                                <p xml:id="auto_vivjcmt6">
                                    What is the acceleration of the vehicle?
                                </p>
                            </li>
                            <li xml:id="auto_d9wvdcaa">
                                <p xml:id="auto_cf7norx2">
                                    Is the acceleration positive or negative? Why?
                                </p>
                            </li>
                        </ol>
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ol>
        </p>
        
    </activity>

    <exploration xml:id="exploration-constant-acceleration">
        <title>Motion with Constant Acceleration</title>

        <introduction xml:id="auto_9x79c815">
            <p xml:id="auto_res9xh9o">
                In this activity, you will explore how the motion of an object changes when it moves with 
                <em>constant acceleration</em>. The simulation shows a car moving along a straight road. 
                You can adjust the <em>initial velocity</em> (<m>u</m>) and the <em>acceleration</em> (<m>a</m>) 
                using the sliders. As the car moves, the simulation displays its <em>position</em>, 
                <em>velocity</em>, and <em>distance traveled</em>.
            </p>

            <p xml:id="auto_8t1sl5gw">
                Use the controls to investigate how acceleration changes the motion of the car and how the 
                equations of motion describe this behaviour.
            </p>
        </introduction>

        <figure xml:id="fig-acceleration-motion">
            <caption>
                Interactive simulation of motion with constant acceleration. Adjust the initial velocity 
                and acceleration to observe how the car’s position and velocity change over time.
            </caption>

            <interactive xml:id="interactive-acceleration-motion"
                platform="jsxgraph"
                width="90%"
                aspect="4:3"
                source="jsxgraph/acceleration-motion.js">

                <slate xml:id="jsxgraph-acceleration" surface="jsxboard" aspect="4:3"/>

                <instructions xml:id="instructions-acceleration-motion">
                    <p xml:id="auto_3ii4gb5y">
                        <ol>
                            <li xml:id="auto_ff9lbs24">Use the slider labeled <q>Initial velocity</q> to set the starting speed of the car.</li>
                            <li xml:id="auto_q19w0xvh">Use the slider labeled <q>Acceleration</q> to control how quickly the car’s speed changes.</li>
                            <li xml:id="auto_uoo4ofm3">Click <c>Start</c> to begin the animation.</li>
                            <li xml:id="auto_wxye3fyy">Observe the arrow above the car. This arrow represents the <em>velocity</em> of the car and changes length as the speed increases.</li>
                            <li xml:id="auto_8i5enpq1">Watch the dotted line and the label above the car to see how the <em>distance traveled</em> changes with time.</li>
                            <li xml:id="auto_jbs6dsb1">Click <c>Pause</c> at any time to examine the car’s position, velocity, and time.</li>
                            <li xml:id="auto_xkdawlrv">Click <c>Resume</c> to continue the motion.</li>
                            <li xml:id="auto_r0wto9i4">Click <c>Reset</c> to restart the simulation and try a different combination of initial velocity and acceleration.</li>
                        </ol>
                    </p>

                    <p xml:id="auto_8aqnumvs">
                        Use the simulation to investigate the following questions:
                        <ol>
                            <li xml:id="auto_5wj03wa3">
                                <p xml:id="auto_k7u5j29a">
                                    Set the acceleration to <m>0</m>. Start the animation. 
                                    How does the car move when there is no acceleration? 
                                    What happens to the velocity arrow?
                                </p>
                            </li>

                            <li xml:id="auto_72b78ztd">
                                <p xml:id="auto_mmbxt5cw">
                                    Keep the initial velocity the same but increase the acceleration. 
                                    How does the speed of the car change over time?
                                </p>
                            </li>

                            <li xml:id="auto_k5hz2nso">
                                <p xml:id="auto_nm7y11pm">
                                    Pause the animation after a few seconds. 
                                    Compare the values of <em>velocity</em>, <em>time</em>, and <em>position</em>. 
                                    How does acceleration influence how quickly the velocity increases?
                                </p>
                            </li>

                            <li xml:id="auto_yay1mzd8">
                                <p xml:id="auto_ecnhjd7j">
                                    Try a larger acceleration value. 
                                    How does this affect how quickly the car moves across the screen?
                                </p>
                            </li>

                            <li xml:id="auto_vj9mqh8s">
                                <p xml:id="auto_gcg2u16l">
                                    Based on your observations, explain why the distance traveled by the car 
                                    depends on both the initial velocity and the acceleration.
                                </p>
                            </li>
                        </ol>
                    </p>
                </instructions>

            </interactive>
        </figure>
    </exploration>
    <insight xml:id="auto_yyhki9i0">
        
        <p xml:id="auto_y5pm1rel">
           <term>Acceleration</term> - The rate of change of velocity with time. SI unit is <m>m/s²</m>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_dfrmr3em">
            Acceleration is given by
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_1tt260ir">
            <md>
                <mrow>\text{Acceleration} \, = \frac{\text{Change in velocity}}{\text{Time Taken}} </mrow>
            </md>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_ouylhuil">
            <md>
                <mrow> a = \frac{\Delta v}{\Delta t} </mrow>
            </md>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_x6rw3id1">
            
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_b7mw6hk6">
            Negative acceleration is called <term>deceleration or retardation</term>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_5a2ntn7r">
            For motion with <term>constant acceleration</term>, the three equations of motion are:
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_3kfvzhfb">
            <ol xml:id="auto_pmgr2vyf" marker="i).">
                <li xml:id="auto_eoxk5bo5">
                    <p xml:id="auto_dkk07fpc">
                        <m>\text{final velocity}</m> = Initial velocity + (acceleration <m> \times </m> time)
                    </p>
                    <p xml:id="auto_d5yhnoma">
                        <m> v = u + at</m>
                    </p>
                    <p xml:id="auto_tt4elbrs"> where;
                        <ul xml:id="auto_lt53oxrt">
                            <li xml:id="auto_vhr311lp">
                                <p xml:id="auto_bo05lifx">
                                    <m>v</m> is Final velocity
                                </p>
                            </li>
                            <li xml:id="auto_4p3m3djg">
                                <p xml:id="auto_mhnv9i5q">
                                    <m>u</m> is initial velocity
                                </p>
                            </li>
                            <li xml:id="auto_klguyusx">
                                <p xml:id="auto_csk607yp">
                                    <m>a</m> is acceleration
                                </p>
                            </li>
                            <li xml:id="auto_5psa3cw6">
                                <p xml:id="auto_3qgr6kv7">
                                    <m>t</m> is time
                                </p>
                            </li>
                        </ul>
                    </p>
                </li> 
                <li xml:id="auto_39aybthh">    
                    <p xml:id="auto_5fnj9t86">
                     Displacement = <m>(\text{initial velocity} \times \text{time}) + (\frac{1}{2} \times \text{acceleration} \times \text{time}^2) </m>
                    </p>
                    <p xml:id="auto_nqmwkfvi">
                        <m> s = ut + \frac{1}{2} at^2 </m>
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_fc3pvhs1">    
                    
                    <p xml:id="auto_9qgfk9fk">
                        <m>\text{Final velocity}^2 = \text{Initial velocity}^2</m> + (2 <m>\times</m> acceleration <m>\times</m> displacement)
                    </p>
                    <p xml:id="auto_ih8iv2l9">
                        <m>v^2 = u^2 + \, (2 \times \textbf{acceleration}) \times s^2</m>
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ol>
        </p>
    </insight>
    <note xml:id="auto_dheq38vn">
        <p xml:id="auto_2ptg2aum">
            Deceleration is donated by a negative sign in the acceleration value. 
            For example: if the deceleration is <m>5 \, \text{m/s}^2</m>, then it's acceleration is <m>-5 \, \text{m/s}^2</m>.
        </p>
    </note>

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Phase 2: Formalizing Acceleration Concepts</title>
        <dl>
            <li xml:id="auto_bobfj7vp">
                <title>Suggested Time</title>
                <p xml:id="auto_mmcwmlal">
                    10 minutes
                </p>
            </li>
            <li xml:id="auto_82wqyvdz">
                <title>Grouping</title>
                <p xml:id="auto_ycot7bwd">
                    Whole class
                </p>
            </li>
            <li xml:id="auto_xd7ck5se">
                <title>Scaffolding Strategies to Address Misconceptions</title>
                <p xml:id="auto_22l81jzh">
                    <ul>
                        <li xml:id="auto_2rscgzt7"><p xml:id="auto_cp7wu5uy"><alert>Misconception:</alert> Acceleration means going fast. <alert>Clarification:</alert> Acceleration is the <em>change</em> in velocity, not the velocity itself. An object can have high speed but zero acceleration (constant velocity).</p></li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_7j9j9ar9"><p xml:id="auto_9n2bbm7o"><alert>Misconception:</alert> Negative acceleration means no movement. <alert>Clarification:</alert> Negative acceleration (deceleration) means the object is slowing down, not that it has stopped.</p></li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_3bkfujeg"><p xml:id="auto_vg3zme5d"><alert>Misconception:</alert> The three equations of motion work for all motion. <alert>Clarification:</alert> These equations apply only to motion with <em>constant</em> acceleration.</p></li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_r9rget42"><p xml:id="auto_3kp1qg6o"><alert>Misconception:</alert> Units of acceleration are m/s. <alert>Clarification:</alert> The unit is m/s<m>^2</m> (metres per second squared) because acceleration measures change in velocity per unit time.</p></li>
                    </ul>
                </p>
            </li>
        </dl>
    </axiom>

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Phase 3: Practice and Application</title>
        <dl>
            <li xml:id="auto_9ijp7h3t">
                <title>Suggested Time</title>
                <p xml:id="auto_elj3pdak">
                    15 minutes
                </p>
            </li>
            <li xml:id="auto_t0pih0t2">
                <title>Grouping</title>
                <p xml:id="auto_djz8k5n4">
                    Individual, then pairs for checking
                </p>
            </li>
            <li xml:id="auto_n6273xtx">
                <title>Teacher's Role</title>
                <p xml:id="auto_f9n7tgb0">
                    Walk through the first worked example on the board, emphasising the use of <m>v = u + at</m>. Then allow students to attempt the remaining examples independently. Circulate to check working and ensure students correctly identify initial velocity, final velocity, and time before substituting into formulas.
                </p>
            </li>
        </dl>
    </axiom>
     <example xml:id="auto_7r51tqq3">
        <statement>
            <p xml:id="auto_ihxm0p6i">
                A car starts from rest and accelerates at 2 m/s² for 5 seconds. Find its final velocity.
            </p>
        </statement>    
        <solution>
            <p xml:id="auto_prjm3xmz">
                <m> v = u + at  </m>
            </p>  
            <p xml:id="auto_kinl36rk">
                <m>= 0 + (2 \times 5) = 10 \, \text{ m/s}</m>
            </p> 
            <p xml:id="auto_covd04mc">
                The final velocity is <m>10 \, \text{ m/s}</m>
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>
    <example xml:id="auto_x5b3mdje">
        <statement>
            <p xml:id="auto_0smtw0yu">
                A rocket accelerates from rest to <m>250</m> m/s in <m>10</m> seconds. Calculate the rocket's acceleration.
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p xml:id="auto_qp2a12lj">
                Initial velocity  <m>u = 0 </m>m/s
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_jrc0azwj">
                Final velocity  <m>v = 250 </m>m/s
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_u0ox1eqy">
                Time (t) = <m>10 </m>seconds
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_s1di0myv">
                Acceleration (a) = (v - u) / t
                <md>
                    <mrow> \frac{(v - u)}{t} </mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_j3edz8e7">
                <md>
                    <mrow> a = \frac{(250- 0 )\,\text{m/s}}{10 s} </mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_cjy15jkb">
                <md>
                    <mrow> a = \frac{(250 \, \text{m/s})}{10 \, \text{s}}</mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_zi7h8ske">
                <md>
                    <mrow> a = 25 \, \text{m/s}^2</mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_eif274rx">
                The rocket's acceleration is <m>25 \, \text{m/s}^2</m>
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>
    <example xml:id="auto_e7k2g744">
        <statement>
            <p xml:id="auto_x04wk05q">
                An object decelerates from 20 m/s to 5 m/s in 3 seconds. What is its acceleration?
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p xml:id="auto_2d7veccb">
                Initial velocity  <m>u = 20 </m>m/s
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_mc9n4lhe">
                Final velocity  <m>v = 5 </m>m/s
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_52nyws1i">
                Time (t) = <m>3 </m>seconds
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_16rrr350">
                Acceleration (a) = (v - u) / t
                <md>
                    <mrow> \frac{(v - u)}{t} </mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_mevskiyd">
                <md>
                    <mrow> a = \frac{(5  - 20 ) \, \text{m/s}}{3 \, \text{seconds}} </mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_fh2ww80z">
                <md>
                    <mrow> a = \frac{(-15 \, \text{m/s})}{3 \, \text{seconds}}</mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_q5hrreyw">
                <md>
                    <mrow> a = -5 \, \text{m/s}^2</mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_zah2icrd">
                The object's acceleration is  <m>-5 \, \text{m/s}^2</m>. The negative sign indicates deceleration (slowing down).
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>
    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Phase 4: Assessment <mdash/> Exit Ticket</title>
        <dl>
            <li xml:id="auto_o75ghb3b">
                <title>Suggested Time</title>
                <p xml:id="auto_oieliqn9">
                    5 minutes
                </p>
            </li>
            <li xml:id="auto_87euo574">
                <title>Grouping</title>
                <p xml:id="auto_9elko0li">
                    Individual
                </p>
            </li>
            <li xml:id="auto_zdynw79a">
                <title>Exit Ticket Questions</title>
                <p xml:id="auto_iw9ziyjo">
                    <ol marker="1.">
                        <li xml:id="auto_tta367iq"><p xml:id="auto_ejmcuwhr">A car's velocity changes from <m>10</m> m/s to <m>30</m> m/s in <m>4</m> seconds. Find its acceleration.</p></li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_93kilduz"><p xml:id="auto_esrartc7">A car moves with <m>8</m> m/s<m>^2</m> acceleration for <m>5</m> seconds, reaching <m>40</m> m/s. Find its initial velocity.</p></li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_2hz80yi1"><p xml:id="auto_3bjxttjq">A cyclist's speed increases from <m>5</m> m/s to <m>17</m> m/s over <m>6</m> seconds. What is the cyclist's average acceleration?</p></li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </li>
            <li xml:id="auto_bpmhzgiq">
                <title>Answer Key</title>
                <p xml:id="auto_zdnhs4yt">
                    <ol marker="1.">
                        <li xml:id="auto_vtfavk68"><p xml:id="auto_tk4h7krg"><m>a = \frac{30 - 10}{4} = 5</m> m/s<m>^2</m>.</p></li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_5vpwx4ze"><p xml:id="auto_rxfu2rch"><m>u = 40 - (8 \times 5) = 0</m> m/s.</p></li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_993z1xym"><p xml:id="auto_bupywn47"><m>a = \frac{17 - 5}{6} = 2</m> m/s<m>^2</m>.</p></li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </li>
        </dl>
    </axiom>

    <exercises xml:id="exercises-linear-motion-velocity-and-acceleartion">
        <exercise xml:id="auto_azsvzifp">
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_shkv4idk">
                    A car's velocity changes from <m>10 \, \text{m/s}</m> to <m>30 \, \text{m/s}</m> in <m>4</m> seconds. Find its acceleration.
                </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p xml:id="auto_r7e82uk7">
                    <m> a = \frac{(30 \, \text{m/s} - 10 \, \text{m/s})}{4 \, \text{s}} = 5 \, \text{m/s}^2 </m>
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>
        <exercise xml:id="auto_yewaxuly">
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_ghmbjij3">
                    A car moves with <m>8 \, \text{m/s}^2</m> acceleration for <m>5</m> seconds, reaching <m>40 \, \text{m/s}</m>. Find its initial velocity.
                </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p xml:id="auto_1p2iqhux">
                    <m> u = 40 \, \text{m/s} - (8 \, \text{m/s}^2 \times 5 \, \text{s}) = 0 \, \text{m/s} </m>
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>
        <exercise xml:id="auto_lncaaj3c">
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_vpomt98c">
                    A train moving at <m> 40 \, \text{km/h} </m> decelerates at <m>0.5 \, \text{m/s}^2</m>.  Find the time taken to stop
                </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p xml:id="auto_4gxqtl38">
                    <m> t = \frac{(0 \, \text{m/s} - 11.11 \, \text{m/s})}{-0.5 \, \text{m/s}^2} = 22.22 \, s </m>
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>
        <exercise xml:id="auto_9be8e60c">
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_mnr51uxu">
                    A cyclist's speed increases from <m> 5</m> m/s to <m>17</m> m/s over a period of <m>6</m> seconds. What is the cyclist's average acceleration?
                </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p xml:id="auto_7awojser">
                    <m> a = \frac{(17 \, \text{m/s} - 5 \, \text{m/s})}{6 \, \text{s}} = 2 \, \text{m/s}^2 </m>
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>
        <exercise xml:id="auto_n5ef1pgc">
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_8ps76esm">
                    A runner's velocity changes from  <m>3</m> m/s to <m>7</m> m/s. What is the runner's average velocity?
                </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p xml:id="auto_6hn5lr45">
                    <m> \text{Average velocity} = \frac{(3 \, \text{m/s} + 7 \, \text{m/s})}{2} = 5 \, \text{m/s} </m>
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>
    </exercises>

